This could also be proved by copying `small_Iio`, `small_Iic` and `not_small_ordinal` to nimbers and then stating that this set is too small,
```lean
theorem add_nonempty (a b : Nimber.{u}) :
    {x | (갞 a' < a, a' + b = x) 갿 갞 b' < b, a + b' = x}尻.Nonempty := by
  simp_rw [Set.nonempty_compl, Set.setOf_or,  Set.mem_Iio,  Set.image.eq_1]
  apply_fun (fun a : Set Nimber  Small.{u} a)
  have : Small.{u} ((췅 + b) '' Set.Iio a 걁 (a + 췅) '' Set.Iio b) := inferInstance
  simp [this, small_congr (Equiv.Set.univ _)]
  exact not_small_nimber
```
I'm not sure what's cleaner.
`blsub` is some code stink that should eventually be removed, all it really does is codify the fact that `Iio o 칑 Iio o` is a small type. So I'm glad to replace it by an argument using `Small`.

```suggestion
protected theorem add_comm (a b : Nimber) : a + b = b + a := by
  rw [add_def, add_def]
  simp_rw [or_comm]
  congr! 7 <;>
  (rw [and_congr_right_iff]; intro; rw [Nimber.add_comm])
termination_by (a, b)
```
Perhaps it's more symmetrical to take `a + b + c  0` instead of `a  b + c`?

I agree, but this lemma is meant to match [`Nat.xor_trichotomy`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Nat/Bitwise.html#Nat.xor_trichotomy) which uses this same assumption.

What do you think about refactoring that theorem too?
That sounds like a good idea

In fact, I could make the statement even more symmetrical by changing it to
```
b + c < a 갿 c + a < b 갿 a + b < c
```
Shouldn't `add_cancel_right` and `add_cancel_left` be `@[simp]`?
Sure thing.
I don't think this should be a simp lemma. For comparison, `sub_eq_zero` isn't `@[simp]`.
Perhaps this should be called `add_eq_zero`, to match `sub_eq_zero`?

```suggestion
theorem not_small_nimber : 춻 Small.{u} Nimber.{max u v} :=
```
This is `Nimber.not_small_nimber` compared to `_root_.not_small_ordinal`, I think this should be outside the namespace.
Could you also transfer `Ordinal.small_Iic`?
Sure. It'd be nice to be able to infer `Small (Set.Iic a)` (and the other intervals) from `Small (Set.Iio a)` and `NoMaxOrder`.
Let's move this TODO to the list of others at the top

It would also be nice to relate the bitwise `xor` definition on naturals to the addition you've defined here. Something like, doing `xor` on naturals then embedding into nimbers is the same as embedding into nimbers then adding

This shouldn't be too difficult to prove using induction plus [`Nat.lt_xor_cases`](https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/Data/Nat/Bitwise.html#Nat.lt_xor_cases), but it does require porting some of the API of `Ordinal.natCast` over, so I'll do it in a separate PR.

Something that might also be good to do in said PR is introduce the notation `갱x` for `Ordinal.toNimber x`.

```suggestion
  simpa [this, small_congr (Equiv.Set.univ _)] using not_small_nimber
```
looks like it might work, and eliminates a non-terminal simp.
If it doesn't work, then try to eliminate the non-terminal simp in some other way
This seems worth investigating further - can leave that to another pr though
